A lightweight, cross-platform XML configuration file reading library that
uses no extra memory unless the client application requests it.

To achieve zero-allocation operation the library maps the file to a memory
region and walks the XML tree every time a new node is accessed. XML
processing may be slightly slower this way, but application memory will not
get fragmented.

Memory is only allocated to satisfy client requests. In all cases the client
application can supply a pre-allocated buffer to store XML data for further
processing.

A separate caching option is available that builds a node tree when an XML
file is opened. Node searches are then much faster at the cost of a small
amount of memory — 48 bytes per XML node on a 64-bit machine.
